  "text": "It is not clear whether subtle changes in topography disrupt normal adaptive sensory processing, as seems to be the case following major disruptions in sensory organization following nerve transection ), limb amputation (Doetsch 1998), or dystonia [CITATION_1] . However, a sensitive quantitative measure of topography following injury, especially when correlated with sensitive behavioral measures of recovery, will contribute to our understanding of the functional significance of somatotopic organization in sensory cortex and the extent that deviations in topography can place constraints on rehabilitation and recovery after peripheral nerve injury.",
